DESCRIPTION OF THE ORIGINAL PAINTING:
This painting depicts London during the Jacobite Rebellion in 1746. Toward the end of 1745 concerns were raised that the capital would be undefended in the event of a
Jacobite attack. William Augustus
column40:
decided to garrison troops to the north of the city as a precaution. In the
foreground soldiers can be seen assembling at the Tottenham Court Road turnpike. In the distance more troops are shown marching ahead up the Hampstead Road to
make camp at Finchley. In this painting Hogarth contrasts the drunken soldiers in the foreground with the disciplined soldiers marching into the sunlight in the background.
Hogarth is clearly showing both sides of soldiery in this painting
column42:
who is alleged to have remarked ‘does the fellow mean to laugh at
my guards?’
Hogarth decided to organise a lottery wherein those subscribers who paid three shillings above the standard rate for a print would have the chance to win the original
painting. After the subscription closed Hogarth gave the remaining 167 unsold lottery tickets to the Foundling Hospital. One of these tickets
column44:
was drawn from
the box and Hogarth personally delivered the painting to the Hospital Governors on the night of 30 April 1750. George II\'s son
column45: the Duke of Cumberland
column46:
was a Governor
of the Foundling Hospital.

column24: 'This painting depicts London during the Jacobite Rebellion in 1746. Toward the end of 1745 concerns were raised that the capital would be undefended in the event of a\nJacobite attack. William Augustus
column27:
decided to garrison troops to the north of the city as a precaution. In the
foreground soldiers can be seen assembling at the Tottenham Court Road turnpike. In the distance more troops are shown marching ahead up the Hampstead Road to
make camp at Finchley. In this painting Hogarth contrasts the drunken soldiers in the foreground with the disciplined soldiers marching into the sunlight in the background.
Hogarth is clearly showing both sides of soldiery in this painting
column29:
who is alleged to have remarked ‘does the fellow mean to laugh at
my guards?’
Hogarth decided to organise a lottery wherein those subscribers who paid three shillings above the standard rate for a print would have the chance to win the original
painting. After the subscription closed Hogarth gave the remaining 167 unsold lottery tickets to the Foundling Hospital. One of these tickets
column31: was drawn from\nthe box and Hogarth personally delivered the painting to the Hospital Governors on the night of 30 April 1750. George II\'s son
column33: was a Governor\nof the Foundling Hospital.'

column25: 'Mischtechnik auf Nussbaumholz, Inv. Nr. 821 - 832, 40 × 40 cm, Lochner ist der bedeutendste Kölner Maler des 15. Jahrhunderts. Die Altarflügel stammen aus der Kirche St. Laurenz in Köln, ihre später abgetrennten Außenseiten befinden sich heute in der Münchner Alten Pinakothek. Wahrscheinlich ergänzten die Münchener und Frankfurter Bilder ursprünglich als Seitenflügel Lochners berühmtes Weltgericht im Kölner Wallraf-Richartz-Museum. In den Szenen kommt Lochners geniale Bildregie ebenso zum Tragen wie sein detailbeflissener Realismus

column26: 1858 (c).\n\nAs the British re-conquered rebel areas they took a terrible revenge on the Indian population. Stories of atrocities were greatly exaggerated by British soldiers and the press
column27: ensuring that retribution was harsh. Trials of any prisoners were arbitrary and brief

column28: Hewson (1630-1660) worked his way up the ranks of the parliamentarian army during the English Civil Wars (1642-1651) and was knighted by Oliver Cromwell in 1658. He was one of King Charles I\'s judges and signed the death warrant. With the restoration of the monarchy imminent in 1660
column29: he fled to the continent. He was not tried as he was never caught.'

column25: published 15 February 1746.\n\nHaving retreated into Scotland in December 1745
column26: Prince Charles Edward Stuart (\'Bonnie Prince Charlie\') was able to reinforce his army. On 28 January 1746 (Modern Calendar, 17 January 1746 Old Style)
column27: British forces under the command of Lieutenant-General Henry Hawley encountered the strengthened Jacobite army near Falkirk.\n\nHawley opened the attack with his cavalry
column28: which were driven back. The Highlanders then charged, Hawley\'s infantry
column29: hampered by heavy rain from using their muskets to full effect
column30: broke and ran. Jacobite casualties were light
column31: but Hawley\'s forces lost over 600 men. The battle lasted little more than 20 minutes'

column26: 1800 (c).\n\nGeneral Fraser\'s body being wrapped for burial on the battlefield
column27: surrounded by grieving officers and men.\n\nDuring the Seven Years War (1756-1763)
column28: Simon Fraser fought at the Siege of Louisbourg and at Quebec under the command of Major-General James Wolfe. A near-relation of a former Jacobite chieftain
column29: he went to North America in 1776
column30: commanding a brigade in the army of Major-General John Burgoyne during the American War of Independence (1775-1783).\n\nThe following year
column31: Burgoyne allowed his army to be encircled by superior American forces at Saratoga. During an unsuccessful attempt to break through the American position
column32: Fraser was mortally wounded by a rifle ball on 7 October 1777 on the ground called Bemis Heights. He died at 8 o\'clock the following morning and was buried in one of the British redoubts. After this battle
column34: 000 of Burgoyne\'s troops were subsequently forced to surrender to the Americans
column35: which marked a turning point in the war.'

column29: 12 October 1857.\n\nCawnpore was a major crossing point on the River Ganges
column31: where the Grand Trunk Road and the road from Jhansi to Lucknow crossed. In June 1857
column33: the Bengal Army sepoys stationed there rebelled
column34: looted the treasury and laid siege to Major-General Sir Hugh Wheeler\'s garrison. Wheeler retreated to a dry earthen entrenchment just outside the city.\n\nOn 25 June
column37: offered safe conduct to the River Ganges for all those inside the entrenchment
column38: and boats to take them down to Allahabad. Wheeler accepted
column39: and two days later the Europeans marched out towards the landing stage (shown here). As they embarked in their vessels
column40: a shot was heard. The Indian boatmen
column42: jumped overboard and made for the shore. Fearful of treachery
column43: the British immediately opened fire. The Nana\'s men replied with grapeshot and the boats were soon full of casualties. Most of the 60 men who survived the short battle were immediately killed by the Nana\'s troops. Wheeler was among the dead.\n\nDespite the title of the work and its depiction of females being slain
column44: most of the women and children survived the attack. They were kept as hostages in the days that followed
column45: but were eventually killed in another

column26: 1680 (c).\n\nWilliam O\'Brien (1638 (c)-1692) spent most of his early life on campaign overseas
column29: 1st Earl of Inchiquin (1614 (c)-1674). In 1659 he accompanied the earl on an expedition to Portugal to fight against the Spanish. Just off the coast at Lisbon they were captured by pirates
column30: and William lost his left eye during the fight. They were held captive in Algiers and
column31: although his father was released shortly afterwards
column32: William was held hostage for almost a year.\n\nIn 1675
column34: William was appointed Captain-General of the King\'s forces in Africa and Governor of Tangier. However
column35: he was absent from his command for a long period and in 1680 he was recalled to London. During the short reign of King James II from 1685 to 1688
column36: Inchiquin\'s anti-Roman Catholic views led to the confiscation of his estates in Ireland
column39: to lead a rebellion of Protestants in Munster. In 1688 he welcomed the arrival of William of Orange in the Glorious Revolution which deposed King James II. He was present with the new king at the Battle of the Boyne (1690).\n\nIn 1690
column40: Inchiquin was appointed Captain General and Governor of Jamaica
column41: but he died only 16 months later in January 1692
column42: worn out by continual attacks on the island by French ships and internal raids by runaway slaves. He is buried in the Parish Church of St Iago de la Vaga
column45: 4th Earl of Inchiquin married Anne
column46: the eldest daughter of George Hamilton
column47: Earl of Orkney and Elizabeth (née Villiers). Anne succeeded her father to the title of Countess of Orkney on his death in 1736.'

column26:
1690.

Mackay (1640 (c)-1692) joined the army in 1660. He served in France and Italy and was part of the French army which invaded the Netherlands in 1672. The following year he married a Dutch woman and became convinced that he was fighting for an unjust cause. Mackay resigned his commission and took up a captaincy in a Scottish regiment in Dutch service. He journeyed to England in 1685 to assist King James II in putting down the Duke of Monmouth Rebellion.

Mackay later broke with James and was one of the officers who supported William of Orange's bid for the crown in 1688. He became Commander-in-Chief of the army in Scotland the following year. Although his forces were defeated at the Battle of Killiecrankie (1689)
column27: MacKay was eventually successful in suppressing the Jacobite cause in the Highlands. He later served at the Battle of Aughrim (1691) and commanded the British division of the Allied army in Flanders. General Mackay was killed at the Battle of Steenkirk in 1692.'

column26: 1643 (c).\n\nColonel John Hutchinson (1615-1664) was a regicide: one of the 59 Commissioners who signed the death warrant of King Charles I in 1649. During the Civil War he joined the Parliamentarian army with his cousin
column28: and led the defence of the city of Nottingham.\n\nOn the Restoration of the monarchy in 1660
column29: many regicides were executed for treason. Others were hunted down and assassinated
column30: exiled or locked up. The bodies of those who had already died
column31: such as Oliver Cromwell and Henry Ireton
column32: were exhumed and then publicly hanged
column33: beheaded and thrown into a pit. Instead
column34: with the help of his wife
column35: John Hutchinson managed to escape with an incredibly light punishment: he lost his position as a Member of Parliament. However
column36: in 1663 he was implicated in an armed rebellion and imprisoned. He died in 1664.'

column4: Auß Oesterreich ob der Ennß/ Wie die Baurschafft die Statt Lintz... belägert...'
column6: Auß Oesterreich ob der Ennß/ Wie die Baurschafft die Statt Lintz... belägert... doch vom Herrn Statthalter... abgetriben worden. Auch wie Herr Obrister Löbel vor Ennß in der Bawrn Läger gefallen... 900. Erlegt... uver 12000. ... zerstreit'
column15: 'Julius Strnadt: Der Bauernkrieg in Oberösterreich im Jahre 1626
column30:
Auß Oesterreich ob der Ennß/ Wie die Baurschafft die Statt Lintz zu beyden Seiten der Tonaw belägert/ biß in den dritten Tag gestürmet/ doch vom Herrn Statthalter endtlich mit Verlust viel hundert Mann abgetriben worden. Auch wie Herr Obrister Löbel vor Ennß in der Bawrn Läger gefallen/ ihnen viel Viech/ sambt allem Geschütz abgejegt/ bey 900. Erlegt/ auch das gantze Läger so uver 12000. Starck zerstreit/ und in die Flucht geschlagen.

The picture shows a person on a hill
column31:
delighted by a flower he is holding in his hand. Another flower is growing just beside his feet. He wears a fancy hat and rather elegant [???] boots and coat.
Does he represent a peasant??? He seems to be in an exalted mood
column32:
which does not fit to the news of the heavy defeat reported in the pamphlet.
The flower he is holding might remind of a wheel. Is this the anticipation of punishment?
Or are these musings completely groundless and the printer simply used a rather nice cut he had and that could be used for any news item...???

column3: 'Erste/ der auffrürischen Bauren im Ländlein ob der Ens/ vermeynte beschützung'
column4: 'Erste/ der auffrürischen Bauren im Ländlein ob der Ens/ vermeynte beschützung. Das ist: Allerverwunderlichste Außtheilung deß Ländleins ob der Ens: Wie sich die Auffrürische Baurschafft/ auff allen seiten/ in überfallung/ einhelliglich zu beschützen'
column13: 'Julius Strnadt: Der Bauernkrieg in Oberösterreich im Jahre 1626
column25:
'Full title:
Erste/ der auffrürischen Bauren im Ländlein ob der Ens/ vermeynte beschützung. Das ist: Allerverwunderlichste Außtheilung deß Ländleins ob der Ens: Wie sich die Auffrürische Baurschafft/ auff allen seiten/ in überfallung/ einhelliglich zu beschützen vermeinen.
Erstlich gedruckt zu Franckfort am Main 1626.
Pamphlet contains the peasants\' ordinance for military self-defense
column26: the division of Upper Austria into the four quarters
column27: and how defensive measures are to be taken
column31:
meaning the leaders they have elected themselves.
The publisher comments on this only
- in the title-sheet by using the terms \"auffrürische\" (insurgent) and \"vermeynte\" (alleged) resp. \"vermeinen\" (suppose)...
- at the end
column33:
saying: \"Worauß dann unschwer zuersehen/ was der rebellischen Rott endlich meinung sey/ und wie der zorn/ auch bey denen so gute Christen geheissen sein wollen/ in eine unsinnige weiß hinauß zu lauffen pflege. Gott gebe daß alle Unterthanen/ die ihnen von Gott vorgesetzte/ hohe und nider Obrigkeit in schuldigsten Ehren halten/ darmit beyder theil ein friedlich und geruhig Leben inn aller Gottseligkeit gegen Gott und Erbarkeit gegen jederman führen möge. Amen.\"
'

'Development and practical of more sophisticated surgical techniques. The flexibility of print making
column25: as demonstrated by the construction and manipulation of these diverse anatomical image
column26: offered publishers and medical practitioners the ability to represent
column28: and disseminate ideas about the body’s hidden interior and its investigation. The prints themselves were vehicles for the kind of hands-on investigation devoted by contemporary practitioners
column30:
in there rule as instruments in the pursuit of knowledge.

Prints and the pursuit of knowledge seeks to demonstrate the critical rule printed image played in representing and enabling knowledge production in the sixteenth century. As seen in the examples provided throughout the catalogue
column35: and instrument makers who gathered and interpreted knowledge of the natural world used printed images and instruments to describe and understand the world. Historians of both art and science have asserted that images were sometimes more effective as description of the nature world then actual specimens were
column36: and served as proxy for the objects themselves. This exhibition seeks to demonstrate that prints were also important tools in the process of inquiry
column37:
fabricated and activated by their makers to serve as dynamic matrices for argumentation and persuasion.
'

column15: is considered the first example of a modern dissection manual and the first true anatomical text. The earliest edition of the work was printed in Padua in 1478
column16: and more than 40 editions exist in total. By the 14th century
column17: the practice of anatomy had come to refer to the dissection of a cadaver according to prescribed rules, Anathomia was intended as a handbook to guide this process. Mondino\'s Anathomia remained the most widely used anatomical text for 250 years (through the 16th century) because it clearly and concisely provided the important technical indications involved in the dissection process
column18:
including the steps involved and the reasoning behind the organization of these procedures.
'

column38: which provide names of individual bones

column40:
which form part of the foot.

column47:
Cliché Bibliothèque nationale de France.  , ,
The events reported in the various publications offered for sale by this itinerant peddler date this print to 1589. In his right hand he holds a view of the January 1589 siege of Orléans. With his left he offers a pamphlet account of the Spanish Armada. In his hat is the "Neu Zeitung from France about the shocking of the Duke of Guise." His box contains accounts of the sieges of Bergen op Zoom (also illustrated in the background behind the peddler) and Wachtendonk. This etching was long attributed to Jost Amman but is now thought to have been made in the Frankfurt workshop of Theodore de Bry.
Jacob Kempner (who figures on the print) is probably a fake publisher...

\nLouis Finson (also Ludovicus Finsonius)
column44:
Flemish painter. He was the son
 of the painter Jacques Fynson (d before 1609) and trained in his 
father's studio in Bruges, the influence of Netherlandish Mannerism is 
strong in his work. At some time early in the 17th century he travelled 
to Italy, he was certainly in Naples by 1608 and may also have 
previously spent some time in Rome. It is not certain whether he was a 
pupil of <a href="http://www.wga.hu/bio/c/caravagg/biograph.html">Caravaggio
column45: \n but he is known to have copied many of Caravaggio\'s works and to have \nowned at least two of his paintings
column46: one of which was the Madonna of the\n Rosary (Vienna
column47: Kunsthistorisches Museum)
column48: which Finson bought with \nAbraham Vinck (1580-1621)
column49:
perhaps as early as 1607.
After 1612 Finson visited Spain and then France
column50:
arriving in Marseille 
early in 1613. He was already a painter of considerable repute and 
continued to enjoy much success in Provence and to command large sums 
for his paintings. From Marseille he was called to Aix-en-Provence by 
Nicolas-Claude Fabri de Peiresc
column51: who commissioned from him a series of \nportraits and altarpieces. For the cathedral of St Sauveur in Aix

commissioned to paint an altarpiece for the main altar of St Trophime in
 Arles. In 1614 Finson travelled to Montpellier and then to Paris, 
arriving there early in 1615

column27: 'Pitt stands beside an altar on which he is burning books and papers. Fox stands behind him
column28: protesting at the sacrifice. Behind them is Time with his scythe drawing aside the \'Curtain of Futurity\' to reveal a row of broken columns (left) at the foot of which lies a woman with a dagger in her heart
column29: the cap of \'Liberty\' beside her. The column on the extreme left is inscribed \'Ruins of the ancient British House of Parliament Destroy\'d An D° [sic] 1784 1785 &amp,c.\' The altar (right) is \'Altar of Slavery erected in a few years By the Unhappy Politician\'. Its face is decorated by three medallions flanked by emblems of slavery: two headsman\'s axes
column32: and rods and chains (right). The largest medallion contains a profile head of George III (the \'Unhappy Politician\'), the others
column34: contain a man being flogged (left) and a man kneeling at a block while the headsman raises his axe. The altar stands on three steps: The lowest and largest is \'Ist Step Dissolving the of the [sic] Parliament of the People\', the next
column35: \'2nd A Venal majority in a packd Parliament\', the uppermost
column36: \'3rd An Open Violation of the rights of Election\'. Pitt is burning \'Manchester Remonstr[ance]\'. \'Magna Cha[rter]\'
column38: and \'Liberty of the Press\'. He turns to Fox
column40: \"The day is mine in spite of your Petitions.\" A mask is slung across his shoulders by a ribbon inscribed \'Duplicity W. Blifil\' implying that Pitt and Fox are typified by the hypocrite Blifil and the honest Tom Jones. Fox holds a \'Petition for redress\'. 8 January 1787 Hand-coloured etching'

column25:
'Thomas Docwra (1458? – 1527) was Grand Prior of the English Knights Hospitaller.

As Grand Prior of St John he served on a number of commissions: he was involved with drainage in Lincolnshire
column26:
where the order had substantial holdings and was brought in on a 
commission to investigate irregularities by the Masters of the Mint. he 
was also connected with the "search for suspicious characters in London"
 in 1520. But perhaps it was his diplomatic activities on behalf of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_VII
column28:
of England\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Henry VII\n and Henry VIII for which he is most remembered. He engaged in marriage \nnegotiations as well as financial and commercial matters. (WIKIPEDIA)
'

column28:
'Captain James Hind (sometimes referred to as John Hind) (baptised 1616 - 1652) was a 17th-century highwayman (who is said to have only robbed Parliamentarians) and Royalist rabble rouser during the English Civil War.

He came from the town of Chipping Norton
column29: Oxfordshire. His partner Thomas Allen was captured when they attempted but failed to rob Oliver Cromwell. He also robbed John Bradshaw
column30:
President of the High Court of Justice for the trial of King Charles I.

When finally caught during the Protectorate Hind was charged with treason rather than highway robbery because of his expressed Royalist loyalty and hanged
column31: drawn and quartered in 1652 at Worcester. He was the subject of a biography The English Gusman by George Fidge (London 1652)

column3: 'Ansicht der Hinrichtung von Johann Friedrich Struensee und Enevold Brandt'
column4: 'Ansicht der Hinrichtung von Johann Friedrich Struensee und Enevold Brandt'
column29: 'Count Johann Friedrich Struensee (5 August 1737 – 28 April 1772) was a German doctor. He became royal physician to the mentally ill King Christian VII of Denmark and a minister in the Danish government. He rose in power to a position of \"de facto\" regent of the country
column30: where he tried to carry out widespread reforms. His affair with Queen Caroline Matilda (\"Caroline Mathilde\") caused scandal
column31: especially after the birth of a daughter
column33:
and was the catalyst for the intrigues and power play that caused his downfall and dramatic death. He died unmarried. (WIKIPEDIA)

German description according to the Bomann-Museum Celle Catalogue:

\"Diese Ansicht der Hinrichtung von Johann Friedrich Struensee und Enevold Brandt zeigt die Situation am 28. April 1772 auf dem Richtplatz vor Kopenhagen. Das für die Hinrichtung aufgestellte Gerüst
column34: wo der Henker und seine Gehilfen ihre schauerliche Arbeit verrichten
column35:
wird von einer großen Menschenmenge umrahmt.\"
'

DE" lang="EN-US">78th Fraser Highlanders was raised in Scotland in 1757 to fight in North
America during the Seven Years War (1756-1763). Simon Fraser
column27: \nand son of the 11th Lord Lovat who was executed for his part in the Jacobite\nRevolt of 1745-1746
column28: was commissioned as its lieutenant-colonel. His regiment\ntook part in the capture of Louisbourg in 1758
column30: the capture of Montreal in 1760 and the Battle of Signal Hill in 1762. It was disbanded at the end of the war in 1763.

column25:

mso-fareast-font-family:&quot,Times New Roman&quot,,mso-ansi-language:EN-US,mso-fareast-language:
DE" lang="EN-US">This silver medal depicts the English lion trampling on an Irish wolfhound
and clawing at a French cockerel. The Irish and French suffered a serious
defeat at the hands of King William III's army at Aughrim
column27: in July\n1691. The battle was one of the bloodiest fought on Irish soil - over 7
column28: 000 men were killed. It marked the end of the Irish Catholic Jacobite resistance to William. The Latin inscription on the medal translates as: 'Thus with one claw he strikes two. The rebels and the French defeated near Aughrim'.
column29:
",serif",,\nmso-fareast-font-family:",Times New Roman",,mso-ansi-language:EN-US,mso-fareast-language:\nDE\" lang=\"EN-US\">
The lion had been a symbol of English royalty since the twelfth century
column30: \nwhile the wolfhound was an ancient icon of the Kings of Ireland. The cockerel\nhas long been a symbol of France thanks to its qualities of vigilance
column31: courage\nand fighting spirit. Originally a royal symbol
column32: the bird became a popular\nemblem during the French Revolution
column33: but fell out of favour during Napoleon\'s\nreign. He was not convinced that a farmyard animal was a suitable regal emblem\nand replaced it with an eagle.

This silver tankard commemorates William Augustus
column26: Duke of Cumberland\'s victory over\nCharles Edward Stuart
column28: grandson of the exiled King\nJames II
column29:
and his Jacobite army at Culloden in Scotland on 16 April 1746. Culloden ended the Jacobite Rebellion of 1745-1746.

Convinced that harsh measures were required to suppress the uprising
column30: Cumberland\'s\ntreatment of his beaten enemy was ruthless. His men searched cottages for\nrebels
column32:
earning their commander the nickname 'Butcher'.

Culloden was the last pitched battle fought on British soil and a key moment in the 'Making of Britain'. It brought long-lasting stability to British politics and
column33: \nby depriving the French of the opportunity of causing trouble for the\nGovernment in its own back yard
column34: paved the way for global conquest. It also\nsafeguarded the succession of the Protestant House of Hanover
column35: the ancestors of our present Queen.

Abbildung der Statt Linz/ wie dieselbe von den Bawren biß an dritten Tag beschossen und gestürmbt/ biß sie auch ein Loch in die Mawr geschossen/ Doch aber durch Herrn Statthalters wolverordnete Soldaten/ mit grossem verlust der Bawren/ sieghafft abgetrieben/ deren etlich hundert darnider gehawen/ theils gefangen/ und die ubrige in die Flucht gejagt.
column34:
250x315

Picture shows how the peasants have perforated the wall of the city at the right-hand side
column35: not far from the church. Many of them have entered the city and want to storm and occupy it. Some annotations can be found within the picture
column36: interestingly they are mirror-inverted and since they are rather blurred
column37: it is hard to decipher them. But apparently they read: Die Bauren
column39: and for the first one among those running into the city again \"Bauer\" (peasant). They are faced by men on horseback. And the first one who comes to their encounter is describted as Stathalter (the steward
column41: what is going on. The peasant are confident to have made the breakthrough and to conquer the city
column42: but Herberstorff is well-prepered and his most experienced soldiers welcome the peasants
column43: who have no space to dodge. Many of them are slaughtered or captured
column44: and it is quite evident that Herberstorff could have had them killed altogether. But he stops short. He \"is not keen on peasant blood\"
column45: but he releases and exhorts them to return to obedience. The peasants are grateful and promise to try to persuade the others outside to stop the siege of the capital and better go home. \"Which might happen soon
column46:
when they see the distress". ,

'This title-page shows Britain covered in the clouds of war and destruction. But heavenly light is cast from above to end the troubles. Justice is seated on the right hand side with a sword and scales.
'

column26: 'This title-page shows an allegory of the church
column27: holding the keys of St. Peter
column28: a cross as sign of the faith and religious books. She is seated between a lion and a seven-headed beast. Two men underneath represent the contrasting yet complementary styles of life attributed to Abel and Cane in the Bible: one man holds a lamb on his shoulder and represents the man of the wilderness
column29: while the other one is depicted as a farmer. Two ovals at the very bottom show animals savely enclosed on a pasture (on the left) and animals disturbed and scattered (on the right)
column30:
which might me be read as symbols of the church as God\'s flock.
'

column4: Empires and Principallities of the World'
column6: Empires and Principallities of the World'
column27: 'This title-page shows female representations of the four known continents (Europe
column29: Asia and America) and stereotypically depicts rulers / warriors from each region. Four fighting animals at the bottom of the print show that the continents obviously are competing with each other. Europe is depicted as a horse
column30: Africa is depicted as a lion
column31: Asia is depicted as an elephant
column32: and America is depicted as a wild cat (?). The full title reads: \"The Estates
column34: Represented by ye description of the Countries
column39:
Religion and the Princes that haue gouerned in euery Estate. With the description of all Miliarie and Religious Orders. Translated out of French by Ed. Gruinstone. Sargeant at Arms.\"

column24: 'This frontispiece depicts the king placing his \'sacred\' hands on his pleading subjects. Anglican priests in liturgical garments stand next to the throne and pray. Members of the royal family and court are also present. In the foreground

column29: 'Sarah Malcom was convicted and hanged for the murder of an elderly widow. Portraits of famous criminals were very popular in 18th century Britain and often sold shortly before the executions. This sheet by Hogarth was priced at 6 pence. In general terms
column30: the purpose of producing such portraits was to capitalise on the topicality of the event and the notoriety of the criminal. Moreoever
column31: Malcolm\'s life represented the kind of cautionary narrative that Hogarth utilised within Industry and Idleness as well as The Four Stages of Cruelty. Malcom was executed in Fleet Street in March 1733
column32: before a huge crowd of onlookers. Although she had confessed to the robbery

column45:

peinlich außzupressen. Unter andern /wie hierbey E verzeichnet ist) [S.170] daß
sie einem die Hände auff den Rücken binden/ in die Höhe ziehen/ und einen
schweren Balcken an die Füsse hängen/ auff welchen der Scharffrichter (F) zum
öftern springet/ und dem Sünder also die Glieder wol auseinander recket, Unter
den Füssen wird darzu ein Fewr angezündet/ welches durch Hitze die Füsse/ und
durch Rauch das Gesichte peiniget/ und lassen bißweilen darzu oben auff den
Kopff/ da sie eine Platte scheren/ halt Wasser treufflen [vgl. das Bild
Razin??? Am Pranger mit Wasser auf die Platte
column47:
check]. Auch nach Beschaffenheit der Sache in solcher positur peitschen/ und über die Wunden mit glüenden Eysen fahren.

[Die Schuldner werden auf die Prawe gestellet] Es wird über nichts so sehr Justitz gehalten/ als über die Schuldner. Wer nicht bezahlen will oder kann/ der wird Pristafet/ das ist: We muß bey eines Richters Knechte im Hause sitzen/ gleich wie bey uns im Gehorsam oder arreste. Erfolget die Zahlung gleichwol nicht/ so wird Er ohne ansehn der Person/ se sey Russe oder Frembder/ Mann oder Weib/ Geistlicher oder Weltlicher/ in den Schuld-Thurm gesetzet/ und täglich eine Stunde vor die Canceley auff einen öffentlichen Platz geführet/ und mit einem schwencken Stecken als eines kleinen Fingers dicke auff die Schienbeine geschlagen/ das die Leute offt wegen grossen Schmertzen überlaut schreyen. Bißweilen thut der Executor
column48:
wenn er poschul bekömpt/ gelinde und Fehlschläge, Etliche stecken auf
wol starck Blech oder Eysen in die Stieffeln vor die [S.171] Schienbeine/
welches die Schläge aufffangen muß. Nach außgestandener solcher Pein und Hohn
muß der Schuldner entweder wieder in den Thurm/ oder Bürgen stellen/ daß er den
andern Tag zu gewisser Zeit/ sich wieder einstellen/ und ferner schlagen lassen
will/ und daß heissen sie auff die Prawe stellen. Wie solche art der Straffe
neben andern generibus supplociorum im Kupfer/ so das Schloß von hinten
praesentiret
column49:
sub lit. A ist angedeutet worden. Ist die Schuld aber groß/ daß der Schuldner durchaus keine Mittel zur Zahlung weiß/ muß Er des Creditoris ewiger Sleve werden/ und dienen.

[Battoki geben] Die andern gemeinen Executiones
column50: so man wieder die Verbrecher ergehen lesset/ seynd\nBattoki
column51:
Nasen auffschlitze/ und die Knud geben. Die Battoki mag ein jeglicher Herr seinem Knechte/ oder dem/ über welchen man nur ein wenig Macht hat/ geben lassen. Es muß der Verbrecher den Rock außziehen/ sich auff den Bauch zur Erden liederlegen. Dann setzen sich ihrer zweye/ einer auff den Kopff/ der ander auff die Beine/ und schlagen mit schwancken Ruten auff den Rücken/ über welches nur das blosse Hembde: und ist anzusehen als wie die Körßner die Felle außkloppen. Hiervon besihe lit. B.

[Die Nasen auffschlitzen] Die Nasen pfleget man denen auffzureissen/ welche wieder Verbott Schnuptobak genossen. Derer etliche/ die also bestraffet waren/ seynd uns offt begegnet.

[Die Knut geben] Die Knut geben/ war für unsern Augen ein barbarische manir zustraffen/ und stehet im Kupffer bey lit. E. Solche Execution habe ich den 24. Sept. Anno 1634 an 8. Mannes und einer Weibes Person/ welche das Großfürstliche Gebot überschritten/ Toback und Brandwein verkaufft hatten/ verüben sehen. Siese musten vor der Canceley ihren Leib biß auff die Hufften entblössen/ und einer nach dem andern sich dem Scharffrichters Knechte über den Rücken legen/ und umb dessen Halß die Arme zusammen schlagen: Die Beine wurden ihm zusammen gebunden/ und von einem andern gehalten/ daß Er sich weder oben noch unten rühren kunte. Hinter dem Sünder stund der Scharfrichter bey 3. Guter Schritte zurücke/ und hieb mit einer langen dicken Knutpeitschen/ was er auß vollen Leibes kräfften vermochte( daß nach jeglichem Hieb das Blut mildiglich vom Rücken herunter lieft/ Dann forne an der Peitschen seynd drey Riemen eines Fingers lang/ von harter ungegerbeter Elendshaut/ die als Messer durchschneiden. Es stund des Richters Diener darbey/ laß auß einem Zettel/ wie viel Schläge ein jeglicher bekommen sollte/ und wenn die beschriebe Zahl erfüllet/ rieff Er: Polno
column52:
es ist gnug. Es bekam aber jeglicher 20. In 26. Das Weib aber kaum 16. Schläge/ und fiehl darüber in Ohnmacht. Ihre Rücken behielten nicht eines Fingersbreit ganze Haut/ sie sahen als wie die geschundene Beister.

Darauff wurde jeglichem/ den Toback-Krämern ein Briefflein mit Toback/ den Brandwein-Brennern eine Flasche an den Halß [S.172] gehänget/ je zwey und zwey mit den Armen zusammen gebunden/ auff beyden seiten geleitet (F) und also ferner zur Stadt hinauß/ und wieder hinein auffs Schloß (bey einer guten halben viertel Meile) gepeitschet. So werden auf etliche/ deren Verbrechen groß/ auff solche manier gantz zu Tode geschlagen/ wie des obgedachten General Scheins Sohne wiederfuhre.

[Die Scharffrichter kauffen und verkauffen ihr Ampt] Man sagte/ daß etlicher gepeitschen Freunde/ das von einem geschlachteten Schaffe noch warmes Fell über des verwundeten Rücken ziehen/ und also wieder heilen sollen. Nach außgestandener Straffe ist der Sünder so ehrlich als andere Leute/ mag mit ihnen wieder umbgehen/ essen und trincken/ wie Er wil: Denn es wird in Rußland solche Infamia nicht so groß/ als bey uns Deutschen/ geachtet, Auch der Scharffrichter wird nicht so unehrlich geschätzet: Sintemal etliche Kauffleute sich darzu begeben/ und selbige Handtierung an sich kauffen sollen sollen/ weil es guten profit gibt. Dann weil diese und andere Executiones auch wolhabende Leute zum offtern trifft/ bekömpt Er nicht alleine Geld von der Obrigkeit/ sondern auch von den Missethäter/ daß Er ihn etwas schonen/ und nicht zu hart tractiren sol. Wann sie dann ein ziemliches darbey auffgeleget / und des Handwercks überdrüssig seyn/ verkauffen sie es wieder an andere."

column5: uppspikat på en påle. Teckning ur Johan Petri Klints \"Den swenska krönicka om Kongungh Göstaffs rigemente ifrån anno 1520 intill 1560\".'
column18: 'In 16th century chronicle by Joen Petri Klint'
column26:
the leader of the Dacke-War in Smaland in 1542-43.

The uprising started in June 1542 with the assassination of more sheriffs and tax collectors. Gustav Vasa underestimated the military prowess of the peasants and sent his German mercenaries to quell the revolt. The landsknechts were
column28: unsuited for battle in the rugged forests and suffered heavy losses. Dacke had devised defensive tactics that allowed the peasants to use their steel crossbows with devastating effect. Dacke's successes helped spread the revolt over all the southern provinces of Sweden. The situation was so serious that the king was forced to sue for peace
column29: and a one-year ceasefire\n was signed on 8. November. During the ceasefire
column30: Dacke was the de facto\n ruler of most of southern Sweden and received offers of foreign support\n from the Elector Palatine
column32:
Elector Palatine">Frederick II (who was the son in law of Christian II and claimed the Swedish throne) and Duke Albrecht of Mecklenburg. He reinstated the ceremonies of the Roman Catholic Church and reopened the cross border trade in the areas under his control. With Danish support Gustav Vasa mounted an invasion of Mecklenburg which neutralised the German threat.

The king broke the ceasefire in January 1543 and sent a new and larger army into the rebellious area. Royal propaganda had been spread to win over the population and turn them against Dacke. Dacke himself had become overconfident after earlier successes and met the Royal army in a pitched battle in March. The trained soldiers fighting on their own terms shattered the peasant army
column33: and Dacke was severely injured. After this defeat
column34:
the\n rebellion was effectively over and Dacke became an outlaw.

Dacke was shot and killed in the high summer of 1543 in the forests \nwhich
column36: surrounded the southeastern border between Sweden \nand Denmark (nowadays southern Swedish provinces Småland and Blekinge).\n According to contemporary sources
column37: he had been injured in both legs by \nhits from the king\'s crossbows during the decisive battle a few months \nearlier
column38:
his forces had been routed and he was likely trying to escape from the king's mercenaries. There is no doubt that he was killed on the spot.

Dacke was executed posthumously
column40: and his limbs were sent for public display in larger \ncommunities that had supported him during the rebellion. Gustav Vasa \nordered the annihilation of Dacke\'s entire family
column41: but showed some \nleniency against those who had given themselves up. Thus
column42:
the unity of the realm was restored.

As a result of the war the king was henceforth more careful when dealing with his subjects. The reliance on foreign mercenaries in the army was reduced in favour of soldiers of Swedish extraction (many of which were recruited in Småland) and this laid the foundation for Sweden's military successes in later wars. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nils_Dacke)

More information is needed about the Klint and his chronicle. For whom was it composed and how far did it circulate?

the first copies were printed in 1539 in Venice.

A faithful reproduction of the map was printed in Rome by Antoine Lafréry in 1572.[2]\n All of the original map\'s copies passed out of public knowledge after \n1574
column14:
and the map was largely forgotten – perhaps because few copies \nwere printed and Pope Paul III asserted a 10-year \"copyright.\" It was later widely questioned whether the map had ever existed.[citation needed]\n

In 1886
column15: Oscar Brenner found a copy at the Bayerische Staatsbibliothek in Munich
column17: another copy was found in Switzerland
column18:
brought to Sweden the following year by the Uppsala University Library, as of 2007 it is stored at Carolina Rediviva. (Wikipedia: carta marina)

'
column31: 'The map was created in Rome by the Swedish ecclesiastic Olaus Magnus (1490–1557)
column32: who arrived on a diplomatic visit for the Swedish government and stayed on
column33:
likely because his brother Johannes Magnus became involved in a religious feud with King Gustav I of Sweden.

It is generally considered that Historia de gentibus septentrionalibus (\"A description of the Northern peoples\")\n printed in Rome
column35:
is an extensive commentary based in part on \nfeatures of the map. The Latin notes were translated by Olaus into Italian (1565) and German (1567).\" (Wikipedia: \"carta marina\").

In the lower right-hand corner Olaus Magnus inserted a drawing revealing his strong determination to put an end to the Protestant reign in his own country Sweden: a mouse gnawing at the rope tying a rampant lion to a heavy stone column. The accompanying text reads: \"Solvit mus laqueis constrictum ut sorte leonis: Sic parvi fortes saepius arte iuvant.\" (Oskar Garstein: Rome and the Counter-Reformation in Scandinavia III: Jesuit Educational Strategy 1653-1622
column36:
p. xvii).
On the map here the text reads: \"En leo terribilis que solvit mus laqueatu sic Magni minima sepe iuvaturope.\"
'

column3: 'Warhafftiger Bericht/ Welcher massen die OberOsterreichschen Bauren des Hertzogs von Hollstein Regiment/ welches ihnen grossen schaden gethan/ bey Neunkirchen unvorsehens uberfallen und geschlagen'
column4: 'Warhafftiger Bericht/ Welcher massen die OberOsterreichschen Bauren des Hertzogs von Hollstein Regiment/ welches ihnen grossen schaden gethan/ bey Neunkirchen unvorsehens uberfallen und geschlagen'
column28: 'In the background the picture shows the defeat of the Holsteinian troops and their flight to Passau on September 19
column29: 1626. In the hills on the left a village or little town is burning
column30: apparently the trace of Holsteinians barbarian deeds against civilians
column31: probably Neukirchen in the woods (am Walde). At the bottom of the hills (still on the left) two units are standing in perfect array
column33: as it seems shielded from view by some trees (or a small wood?). A trech to the right of the peasant units separates them from (apparently Holsteinian) cavalry men
column34: who are fleeing to the right
column35: into the direction of a bigger town
column36: that is identified by the written annotation as Passau. Only a few peasants are attacking and chasing the horsemen with flails. Some of the soldiers have fled into and drawned in the Danube. The river in the front leads from the battlefield on the left to Passau on the right. Battle scene and burning village are all on the far side of the Danube
column37: whereas the entire picture is dominated by am oversized figure on this side. The man\'s garment represents a mixture of peasant and noble culture. His skirt and boots are more or less to peasant style
column40: and hat with panache are requisites of noble culture. While standing with his left hand akimbo and daringly facing the spactator
column41: he is carrying a flail of almost his size in his right. Only at closer inspection one becomes confused by the man\'s feet
column42: since his boots are heading towards his back. It is not clear if this is an error or part of the engraver\'s mockery
column43: indicating how perverted the peasants were.  The flail is the most conspicuous object and this is underlined by the inscription in two rhymed verses
column44: that evokes sorcery and thus seems to revise the whole assessment of the depicted battle scene. It reads: \"This instrument is called a flail
column45: And Passau art quickly dilutes/disperses it.\" [\"Dis Instrument ein Flegl genent
column46: Paßauer kunst lösts auff behent.\"] The sense of this inscription is somehow opaque
column47: though. \"Passau art\" is magic practice for making soldiers invulnerable and undefeatable in battle. It is supposed to have an effect either on the person or on his or his enemy\'s weapons. The problem of the verses is the \"lösts auf\"
column48: which means \"löst es auf\"
column49: i.e. \"dissolves/dissipates/cancels it\". Grammatically \"it\" could be the flail. This would mean that Passau art \"dissolves\" invalidates the flail\'s force. This would sound like an advice to the Holsteinian troops fleeing to Passau: Take the chance and rearm yourself with sorcery in order to be prepared against the peasants\' flails for the next time. The other possible reading would be that the \"it\" does not refer to the preceding verse
column50: but to something represented in the picture
column51: in this case most likely the Holsteinian\'s unites \"dissipated\" (aufgelöst) by the attacking insurgents. In this case the insurgents would be said to have recurred to Passau art and thereby transformed their shabby flails into silver bullets. This is the first reference to the role of magic practice I have found in the peasant war. Later on
column52: especially after the peasants\' defeat
column53: it becomes more and more prevalent. It is said that the peasants had sorcerers in their ranks and their successes were due to their pact with the devil. But sorcery was not necessarily black
column54: i.e. develish magic. As white magic it could also be benign. Depending on this classification of the magic applied
column55:
reference to it was incriminating or not.

column56:
in German):
\"Man hat aus Regensburg vom 16. Sept daß das Hollsteinische Volck fortgezogen/ sich mit den Chur Bayrischen zu conjugiren
column57: wie dann der Herzog von Hollstein ordinantz bekommen/ die Bawren anzugreiffen/ unter wegens aber hat er mit sengen und brennen sonderlich mit den Weibspersonen uber die massen Barbarisch gehauset: Als solches die Bawren vernommen/ haben sie zu ihnen gesandt und gefragt/ ob solches ihrer Key.May. oder dero Commissarien
column58: so in Friedens Tractation zu Ens noch beysamen/ befehlich were/ Darauff sie geantwortet/ weil es Nacht/ müsten ja Liechte haben/ Nachdem solches den Bawern vermeldet worden/ haben sie bey Liechteneck ihre Schanzen mit verdeckten Lauffgräben verlassen/ und sich als flüchtige zurück begeben/ Freytags den Glockenstreich unvermerckt ergehen lasen/ und folgenden Samstag zwey stunden vor Tage das Hollsteinische Volck/ so sich dessen nicht besorget/ bey Neunkirchen uberfallen/ Ob wol die Reuterey angesetzt/ haben sie sich doch in die Gräben verfallen/ und nicht fortrücken können/ Das Fußvolck ist aber geschlagen/ zertrennet/ auff ein Meil wegs verfolgt/ viel in der Tonau ersoffen/ und haben die Bawren 15. Fähnlein bekommen. Der Herzog hat durchs refugium mit den ubrigen 6. Fähnlein sich in Passau salviret
column59: und alle munition
column60: Bagaschi mit Silbergeschirr und vielem Gelde im stich gelassen. Man sagt auch das Chur Beyrische Volck habe an denen in armis gebliebene grossen hauffen Bawren desselben Tages bey Rieth auch etwas tentiret
column61:
aber bey verlust etlicher 100. Mann ubel eingebüsset. Jetzt stercken sich die Bawren je lenger je mehr/ wollen den Paß der Tonau sperren/ dürffte der handel erger als vorhin werden/ wie man sie dann mit aller macht anzugreiffen wiederumb im wercke ist.\"

Translation: \"News coming from Regensburg dated Sept. 16 say
column62: that the Holsteinian\n soldiers have set out to join the troops of the Bavarian Elector and \nthat the Duke of Holstein has got the order to attack the peasants
column63: but on his way he singed and burned what he could and dealt in a particularly barbarian way with women. When the peasants heard about this
column64:
they sent emissaries to ask him if this was on the 
order of His Imperial Majesty or of the Commissions that were still 
negotiating about the conditions of peace in Ens. On which they (the 
Holsteinian troops/ commanders) answered that at night they needed light
 [therefore the fire]. When the peasants were informed about this [answer]
column65:
they left their
hidden entrenchments under Liechteneck and fled back. And on Friday they 
gently rang the church bells [so that the Holsteinians would not suspect that they were summoning their forces] and the following Saturday two hours before
 dawn they assaulted the Holsteinian troops
column66: who camped close to \nNeunkirchen and were surprised by the attack. Even though they tried to \nmobilize their cavalry
column67: it got closed in on the trenches and had no space for movement. The infantry was beaten
column68:
dispersed and chased for about a
 mile. Many drawned in the Danube river and the peasants captured 15 
Fähnlein. The Duke could save himself with the remaining 6 Fähnlein to 
Passau and he had to abandon all his munition
column69: baggage with silver dishes\n and a lot of money. It is also said that Bavarian troops have tried to \nchallenge the peasants
column71: later the same day not far from Rieth
column72:
but that they had 
suffered severe losses of about 100 men. Now the peasants become even 
more eager to block the pass of the Danube. It has to be expected that 
confrontations get more violent than before
column73: since they will also be attacked more rigorously again."

column24:
'A Dutch broadside satirising attempts to negotiate peace in Europe in 
1674 in which the events of the Franco-Dutch war of 1672-78 are 
metaphorically compared to chaos in an alchemist's laboratory. There are
 three kilns or stills. That on the left belongs to the French who feed 
the fire and burn the Christian world (1) with money
column26:
distilling "oil of lilies" (3, French influence?), two 
bottomless baskets of charcoal represent taxes paid by the people (4) 
and the nobility (5) of France and a third contains the products of 
monasteries
column27: royal domains and new levies, stolen Dutch peat (three \nprovinces invaded in 1672) has already been burned. The large kiln in \nthe centre
column28: emblazoned with the double-headed eagle of the Empire
column29: \nbelongs to Cologne, it burns so fiercely with Dutch peat that the doors \nhave had to be opened
column30: and the distillers have to leave. The Dutch still\n (7) is secured by William of Orange
column31: seated in the centre and gesturing\n with his sword towards the still, at his foot lies an ingot labelled \n\"Naerden\"
column32: the town which he has taken from the French. He turns towards\n the \"German alchemist\" (9, perhaps Maximilian Heinrich
column33: Archbishop of \nCologne) who taken had the towns of Lechnich
column39: the latter being pushed \nthrough a sieve
column40: and given them to the \"German master\" (the Emperor). At\n his foot
column41: is a bottle of aurum potabile (10)
column42: the French traitor\'s \ngold
column43: which has been destroyed and a whole basket of abandoned towns and\n strongholds (11): Utrecht
column45: Campen
column47: Amersfoort
column48:
Coevoerden and Nieuweè Schans. The Dutch (12) are using English 
rosewater and the Dutch lion's gunpowder and sea water in the 
traditional way (opening the dykes. Aqua vita is being made for the 
merchants and citizens, aqua fortis for the destroy the gold and steel 
of the enemy. Meanwhile the French are stoking the fire in the Cologne 
kiln (13) so ruthlessly as to blow off the lids of neutrality of three 
jars

Liège and Aachen (14), the liquid evaporates and the heat

Исторического музея и долгое время украшал собой его экспозицию. У него 
очень интересная и даже загадочная история. Я хочу дать слово 
оренбургскому журналисту Вильяму Львовичу Савельзону
column26: автору книг по \nистории родного края. Когда Савельзон собирал материалы к книге «Пушкин и\n Оренбуржье»

он общался с сотрудниками нашего музея. Рассказ Вильяма \nЛьвовича очень яркий и образный. А потом я дополню его \"сухой наукой\".
Материал опубликован 30 марта 2011 года на сайте \"История Оренбуржья\"
http://oxy-lavka.ru/

column105: что \"Портрет дамы\" был написан русским или европейским \nмастером
column106:
хорошо знающим специфическую технику классической европейской масляной живописи на холсте и на темных грунтах. Такая техника была характерна для XVIII века и практически перестала применяться в XIX веке. Технологические особенности живописи портрета дамы соответствуют особенностям живописи этого времени.

В пользу такой оценки свидетельствует следующие факты:
Наличие темных подготовительных слоев (грунта и
column108:
имприматуры).
Различия\n в технике написания светлых и темных живописных деталей
column109:
благодаря \nкоторым темный грунт участвует в формировании оптических свойств темных \nдеталей.

column25: 'This lithography was commanded by John Paul Jones
column26:
printed by order of the Continental Congress and signed by John Hancock.

The New Hampshire Seacoast Visitor Centre calls it \'AMERICA\'S FIRST NAVY POSTER \'. It was published in Portsmouth
column28:
both as a hand-bill and newspaper ad in the NH Gazette. Paul Jones was looking desperately for a crew for the Continental Navy ship RANGER.

 ,"Great Encouragement for Seamen

ALL GENTLEMEN SEAMEN and able-bodied LANDSMEN who have a Mind to distinguish themselves in the GLORIOUS CAUSE of their Country
column30: an Opportunity now offers on board the Ship RANGER
column31: of Twenty Guns (for France) now laying in Portsmouth
column33: commanded by JOHN PAUL JONES Esq,\n let them repair to the ship\'s Rendezvous in Portsmouth
column34: or at the Sign \nof Commodore Maxley
column36: where they will be kindly entertained
column37: \nand receive the greatest Encouragement. -- The Ship Ranger
column38:
in the 
Opinion of every Person who has seen her is looked upon to be one of the
 best Cruizers in America. -- She was ever calculated for sailing 
faster
column39:
and making good Weather.

\n

Any Gentlemen Volunteers who have a Mind to take an agreeable Voyage \nin this pleasant Season of the Year
column41: by entering on board the above\n Ship Ranger
column42: meet with every Civility they can possibly expect
column43:
and for a further Encouragement depend on the first Opportunity being embraced to reward each one agreeable to his Merit.

All reasonable Travelling Expences will be allowed
column44:
and the Advance-Money be paid on their Appearance on Board.

\n

In CONGRESS
column45: March 29
column47: THAT the Marine Committee be authorized to advance to \nevery able Seamen
column48: that enters into the Continental Service
column49: any Sum not\n exceeding FORTY DOLLARS
column50: and to every ordinary Seaman or Landsman
column52:
to be deducted from their future \nPrize-Money.

\n

By Order of Congress
column54:
President.

DANVERS, Printed by E. Russell
column55:
at the House late the Bell-Tavern.\"

The Freeman\'s Journal (NH Gazette)
column56: Portsmouth
column58: July 26
column59:
1777.

ENCOURAGEMENT FOR SEAMEN

Whereas the seamen of these States have for some time past been discouraged from entering into the navy
column60: by thinking they have hitherto been unfairly dealt with \nin respect of prize money
column61: and the regular payment of wages: Therefore
column62: \nto remove all cause of future complaint
column63: I will be answerable to every \nperson who may enter to serve under my command
column64: for the punctual and \nregular payment of wages. And I will also
column65: with the consent and \napprobation of officers and men
column66: appoint an agent for the prizes
column67: whose \nduty it shall be to see the captors part sold to the best advantage
column69:
just and regular payments to every person concern\'d.

\n

Every seaman in the navy is entitled to eight \ndollars per month wages
column70: with an advance of forty dollars at entry on \nboard. Every marine or landsman is entitled to six dollars &amp, two \nthirds per month wages
column71: with an advance of twenty dollars at entry on \nboard. Every private person
column72: who may loose a limb or be disabled in \nengagement
column73: will receive two hundred dollars smart money, if kill\'d
column74: his\n wife or family will receive it. Every person
column76: will receive half pay during life or an allowance \nproportioned to the injury sustained. The pay is extended to persons in \ncaptivity
column77: provided they return to the service as soon as possible. The \ncaptors share one half of all merchant ships
column78: and of all effects taken \nby sea or land
column79: without resistance, they share the whole of all ships of\n war
column80: &amp, of all privateers authorized by his Britannic Majesty to war\n against these States. They will also receive a bounty of twenty dollars\n for every carriage gun then mounted
column81: and of eight dollars per head for \nevery man then on board and belonging to such prizes. There are ten \nshares set apart for the most deserving
column83:
grounded upon resolves of Congress. Persons of abilities will be promoted in proportion to their diligence and merit,-and no equal encouragement can be given in privateers.

The Continental Ship of war Ranger at Portsmouth under my command is in readiness for sea. Such persons as think proper to enter
column84: are requested to apply on board
column85:
or at the Ship\'s rendezvous \nwhere they will receive further information.

\n

Portsmouth

column29:
'This multimedia installation at the National 1798 Rebellion Centre explains the so-called \'great debate\' triggered by Paine\'s and Burke\'s controversial writings. Paine\'s \'Common Sense\' was among the most popular publications in late eighteenth-century Ireland and influenced the agenda of the United Irishmen movement. Burke opposed republicanism and revolutionary tendencies.

column30: Belfast held 3 days of celebrations for Bastille day. The celebrations were officially staged as the Belfast Harp Festival
column31:
a Protestant celebration of Gaelic culture. These celebrations in 1792 were the last occassion on which Protestant and Catholic reformers in Ireland would come peacefully together.

In the decades to come
column32:
Ireland was torn by increasing religious division and the rise of sectarian paramilitarism.

The Orange Order was founded in response to Catholic volunteer forces. Paramilitary organisations quickly spread in late eighteenth-century Ireland and shaped Irish politics of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.

The rise of paramilitarism is an important aspect of the exhibition at the National 1798 Rebellion Centre.

column24: 'The painting is a portrait of Reverend James Wilkinson (1730–1805)
column26: who was affected by the infamous Broomhall Riot in Sheffield in 1791. Although he was an advocate of parliamentary reform and concerned with social issues
column27:
an enraged mob attacked his home when he permitted that a part of the parish graveyard could be used for an extension of Church Street. The riots in Sheffield had initially been triggered by the intended enclosure of 6000 acres of land but were also influenced by the Birmingham Riots of the same year and strong support for the French Revolution among the Sheffield population. Dragoons were sent into town to quell the riots but the mob had already set fire to Wilkinson\'s house and burnt his dining table as well as several books. ,
  • Date painted: 1790s
  • \n

column22:
'The print is discussed on this blog https://mercuriuspoliticus.wordpress.com/tag/pamphlet/ (see text below in description).
Dagmar Freist uses the picture and the title in her book Governed by opinion..
column28:
'

The World Is Ruled &, Governed By Opinion was published \nin 1641 by Thomas Banks (although subsequent editions did not feature \nhis name). , The text is by Henry Peacham
column29:
a writer and illustrator who 
in the late 1630s and 1640s published a number of written works. There 
is some suggestion that he was down on his luck and attempting to make 
money by doing so. At this period Peacham collaborated with Wenceslaus 
Hollar
column30: who is the artist behind the ballad’s illustration. This is one \nof a number of works they collaborated on at this period. The dedication\n is to Sir Francis Prujean
column31:
a noted physician.

\n

In the illustration you can see Opinion (the blindfolded woman)
column32: \ncrowned with the Tower of Babel. She has a globe on her lap
column33:
a chameleon
 on her left arm and a staff in her right hand. In the tree are various 
pamphlets and broadside ballads. On the left is a jester-like man 
watering the tree. On the right is the aristocratic cavalier labelled 
“Viator” or traveller
column34:
who is the person Opinion is debating with in the ballad’s text.

The ballad and its illustration are a good example of of views held in the 1640s about the dangers of print
column35: news and opinion – Opinion is \nan inversion of Justice
column37: producing nothing but \nconfusion and a world turned upside down. This is ironic
column40: was a key producer of cheap \nballads
column41: pamphlets and newsbooks during the 1640s. Paradoxically
column42:
the ballad’s very medium cuts across its message.

Where it gets really interesting are the titles it’s possible to make out of the books hanging from the tree. These are:

  • “[John] Taylor’s Reply”
  • “The Ironmonger’s Answer”
  • “Mercuries Message”
  • “News from Elyzium”
  • “Hellish Parliament”
  • “A Swarme of Sectaries”
  • “Canterburies Tooles” (not Troubles as the British Museum website has it)
  • “Brownists Conventicle”
  • “Taylors Physicke”
  • “Lambeth Faire”

Of these
column45: Taylors Physicke
column46:
and The Ironmonger’s Answer all relate to the pamphlet war between John Taylor and Henry Walker. See: https://mercuriuspoliticus.wordpress.com/2008/07/14/the-pamphlet-war-between-john-taylor-and-henry-walker/

Mercuries Message was a ballad critical of Laud. Newes from Elizium was a satirical piece using the same woodcut of Laud as Mercuries Message. The Hellish Parliament was another satirical pamphlet by Taylor. Canterburies Tooles is a pamphlet purporting to be by Prynne which reused the same woodcut. Brownists Conventicle was yet another Taylor satire. Lambeth Faire was another satirical ballad hostile to Laud.

I have a hunch – and it is no more than that at this stage – that the listed works may all have been published by Thomas Banks. Certainly Taylor had close professional connections with Banks
column47:
who printed a 
number of his satires. And much of Banks’s output at this time consisted
 of cheap satirical pamphlets and ballads. To add another layer of 
paradox
column48: it may be that as well as a critical commentary on the \nburgeoning public sphere in 1641
column49:
The World Is Ruled &, Governed By Opinion is also an advert for the very cheap print the ballad criticises.

What is also potentially fascinating for me is that works from both sides of the pamphlet war between John Taylor and Henry Walker are mentioned – not just Taylor’s but also Walker’s. Having blogged about this previously
column50: and hypothesised that the two may have been closer than is supposed (https://mercuriuspoliticus.wordpress.com/2008/07/20/john-taylor-and-henry-walker-part-4-publishers/)
column51: \n and linked by their mutual associations with Banks and other printers
column52:
it is intriguing to wonder whether Banks actually printed all the pamphlets in the dispute. At any rate it’s something I’ll be following up.

Incidentally the ballad also inspired the title of Dagmar Freist’s excellent study of politics and communication in mid-seventeenth century London
column53: which is now available in limited preview on Google Books (https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aMOXgtjz-I4C&,dq=world+is+governed+by+opinion+freist&,client=firefox-a&,hl=de)
column54:
\n and which I would recommend if you want to find out more about print \nand other forms of communication in 1630s and 1640s London.

'
